%I A395495 #16 May 04 2026 21:19:22
%S A395495 1,3,5,9,13,18,24,31,39
%N A395495 Minimum number of cells in a connected polyomino on the square grid that contains every fixed n-omino as a translated subregion.
%C A395495 Containment is translation-only: the contained piece may not be rotated or reflected. Number of fixed n-ominoes is A001168. Each of a(1) through a(9) is proved via SAT + CEGAR connectivity and carries a DRAT UNSAT certificate at k = a(n) - 1 that is independently verified by drat-trim. A pure-Python geometric containment verifier also re-confirms that every reported container does contain every fixed n-omino as a translate.
%C A395495 Conjecture: a(n) = (n^2 - n + 6)/2 for n >= 4, with a(n) = 2n - 1 for n in {1, 2, 3}. Equivalently a(n) = A000217(n-1) + 3 for n >= 4. Predicts a(10) = 48.
%C A395495 At n = 7 every minimum container has a single 1-cell interior hole. SAT model-enumeration over the 7 X 7 bounding box (the natural search box, which must contain both the horizontal and vertical n-cell I-omino) finds exactly four 24-cell containers; all four are the 25-cell discrete L_1 ball of radius 3 (centered in the 7 X 7 box) minus one cell from the D_4 orbit at L_1 distance 2 from the center, and all contain a hole. A wider 8 X 8 search at k = 23 returns UNSAT (LRAT certified). The hole is therefore a structural feature of a(7), distinguishing this sequence geometrically from the purely numerical match A350660. For n in {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 8, 9} the optimal container is simply connected.
%H A395495 Peter Exley, <a href="https://github.com/pexley-math/oeis-A395495">Solver code, data, and figures</a>, GitHub.
%e A395495 Optimal containers, with one example per illustrated n. Cells are marked '#'; empty cells are '.'.
